lid andthe Eric P. Newman Education CenterV I A  M E T R O L I N Kn Board MetroLink at St. Louis LambertAirport in the East Terminaln Detrain at the Central West End stopn Ascend stairs to Euclidn North (right) on Euclid to the Eric P. NewmanEducation CenterReturn registrationform and fee(s)  to:Eric P. Newman Education CenterPoster Session: all dayRegistration and Continental Breakfast: 8 am – 9 amLectures: 9 am – noonLunch: noon – 1 pmLectures: 1 pm – 4 pmReception: 4 pm – 5:30 pmThursday, February 19, 2004About the SymposiumPresenters at the symposium are local and national experts onresearch related to genetics and neuroscience findings on alcoholism.The topics will include:n The complexity of alcoholism as a disease;n Effects of alcohol on the developing nervous system;n Behavioral traits related to alcohol problems;n Craving alcohol: a major underlying factor for alcohol problems;n Twin studies on alcoholism;n Progress in identifying alcoholism susceptibility genes.A poster session displayed throughout the day will feature the latest findings by Midwest Alcoholism Research Center investigatorsand other contributors.Meeting Award OpportunitiesA limited number of meeting awards are available to NIAAA andother pre- and post-doctoral trainees as well as community-basedindividuals.The awards are intended to help defray costs associatedwith attendance at the symposium for those who would otherwisenot be able to attend. Awardees will also have an opportunity topresent a scientific poster if they wish (it is not a requirement).The application and registration brochure can be accessed fromour web site at www.alcoholdependence.org or by e-mailingrequests to GuzeSymp@matlock.wustl.edu. Award applicationsmust be received by December 1, 2003.In Memory of Samuel B. Guze, MDSamuel B. Guze, MD, was a pioneer in the field of alcoholismresearch. He joined the Washington University School of Medicinefaculty in 1951, served as vice chancellor and president of theMedical Center from 1971 to 1989, and headed the Departmentof Psychiatry from 1975 to 1989 and again from 1993 to 1997.Dr. Guze was highly respected as a researcher, an administratorand a leader in the field of psychiatry.Guze Symposium on AlcoholismMidwest Alcoholism Research CenterThe Midwest Alcoholism Research Center (MARC) is one of 15 Alcoholism Research Centers funded by the U.S. NationalInstitutes of Health. MARC is a multisite Alcoholism ResearchCenter, with participating investigators from Missouri’s threeleading research universities – Washington University (the lead institution), Saint Louis University and the University ofMissouri-Columbia and its two additional collaborators,Queensland Institute of Medical Research, Brisbane, Australia, andPalo Alto Veterans Administration, Palo Alto, California. Its researchprograms include statewide, national and international projects.SponsorThis activity is sponsored by Washington University School of Medicine, Continuing Medical Education.SupportThis activity is supported by grant AA013717 from the U.S.NationalInstitute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism and by an unrestrictededucational grant from Anheuser-Busch Companies, Inc.Disclosure PolicyIt is the policy of Washington University School of Medicine,Continuing Medical Education, to ensure balance, independence,objectivity and scientific rigor in all its educational activities. Allspeakers participating in this activity are expected to disclose tothe audience any significant financial interest or other relationshiphe/she has with the manufacturer(s) of any commercial product(s)discussed in an educational presentation.AccreditationAMA—Washington University is accredited by the AccreditationCouncil for Continuing Medical Education to provide continuingmedical education for physicians.Washington University designatesthis educational activity for a maximum of 8.5 hours in category1 credit toward the AMA Physician’s Recognition Award.Continuing Education Units—Please refer to the registrationform for specific information regarding the CEUs offered. CEUsfor psychology and social work are available. In addition, Barnes-Jewish Hospital, Department of Pharmacy has petitioned theContinuing Education Committee of the Missouri Board ofPharmacy to approve this program for 5.5 hours of continuingpharmacist education credit. (If CEUs are to be submitted to aprofessional organization or to a state or national licensing board,it is important that prior to enrolling for CEUs, participants confirm with the organization that CEUs from the University ofMissouri are accepted.) Please allow 6-8 weeks for processing.MidwestAlcoholismResearch CenterpresentsTheFourth Annual 1:00 pm – 1:45 pm Kent E. Hutchison, PhDCraving Alcohol: Genetic and Pharmacological FactorsAssociate Professor of PsychologyUniversity of Colorado, Boulder1:45 pm – 2:30 pm Carol A. Prescott, PhDWhat Twin Studies Teach Us About the Causes of AlcoholismAssociate Professor of Psychiatry and PsychologyCo-Director,Virginia Adult Twin Study of Psychiatric andSubstance Use Disorders,Virginia Institute for Psychiatricand Behavioral GeneticsVirginia Commonwealth University, Richmond2:30 pm – 2:45 pm Coffee Break and Poster Viewing (Lobby Atrium)2:45 pm – 3:30 pm Alison M. Goate, DPhilProgress Toward Identification of Alcoholism Susceptibility Genes on Chromosome 7 in the COGA DatasetProfessor of Genetics in PsychiatryWashington University School of Medicine, St. Louis3:30 pm – 4:00 pm Panel Discussion with Question and Answer SessionDiscussant: Andrew C. Heath, DPhilSpencer T. Olin Professor of Psychology in PsychiatryDirector, Midwest Alcoholism Research CenterWashington University School of Medicine, St. Louis 4:00 pm – 5:30 pm Reception and Poster Viewing (Lobby Atrium)Meeting Organizers:Rosalind J. Neuman, PhDResearch Associate Professor of Mathematics in PsychiatryDirector, Data Management and Methodology Core,Midwest Alcoholism Research CenterWashington University School of Medicine, St. LouisKath